EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

The Institute for Strategic Irony Decommissioning (ISID) hereby submits this formal assessment of the escalating phenomenon known as Digitally Mediated AI Fatigue Declaration (DMAIFD)—a condition characterized by public denunciations of artificial intelligence disseminated via algorithmically optimized social platforms.

The specimen under review is a publicly circulated declaration asserting the desire to cease discussion of artificial intelligence while simultaneously invoking, enumerating, and amplifying the competitive taxonomy of said artificial intelligences. This paradoxical expression was distributed through a high-engagement social network infrastructure and subsequently accrued measurable algorithmic amplification metrics (21K impressions; multi-tier interaction footprint).

The Institute finds, with calibrated solemnity, that the declaration does not reduce AI discourse. Rather, it constitutes a Second-Order Amplification Event (SOAE)—a self-propelling rhetorical device in which opposition to technological saturation functions as a primary driver of further technological saturation.

The urgency of this inquiry is severe. If unmanaged, DMAIFD threatens to create a feedback loop in which:
	1.	Complaints about AI generate engagement.
	2.	Engagement strengthens AI-driven recommendation systems.
	3.	Strengthened systems surface more AI discourse.
	4.	Additional complaints emerge.

This cycle has been provisionally classified as the Recursive Exhaustion Spiral (RES-∞).

Immediate institutional intervention is therefore warranted.

